indicators.title: PDO 1 Number of technologies that are being made available to farmers and other end users
indicators.description:
Technology refers to the tools, methods or machinery that are used to support agricultural enterprise. There are many categories of agricultural technologies within the production to marketing value chain, and these include mechanical, biological, chemical, and agronomic innovations.  For APPSA new varieties denote those released in the past 5 years since the commencement of the program, i.e. from 2008 onwards.

Availability will be measured by whether seed or agronomic and postharvest practices are being produced and distributed, or a technology has been or is being promoted by the public or private sector. Technologies will be disaggregated by commodity and according to whether they address a cross cutting priority – such as climate change adaptation, gender, nutrition.
“Farmer”: an individual involved in crop and animal production for food, income or raw materials.
“End User”: Consumers/companies that utilize crop and animal produce.

indicators.title: PDO 2 Proportion of Lead Farmers in targeted areas who are aware of an improved technology promoted by the Project
indicators.description:
Lead farmers represent a group of innovative and successful farmers within the local community who are committed to training their fellow farmers on agriculture methods and technologies.
“Targeted areas” - Areas where the project is being implemented.
“Awareness” - Knowing about a technology through extension services and/or other methods of dissemination e.g. field days, agriculture shows, fairs, training.

indicators.title: PDO 3 Number of technologies generated or promoted by the Project in one country that are released in another country
indicators.description:
“Technology generated” - innovation developed.
“Technology promoted” - innovation made available.
“Technology released in another country” - innovation available in at least two countries.

indicators.title: PDO 4 Number of direct project beneficiaries
indicators.description:
Direct beneficiaries refers to the persons (e.g. Lead Farmers, contact farmers, other farmers and their dependent family members living in the same household) in the project target region who in the first instance utilize project outputs (i.e., knowledge, and technologies) AND their immediate household members.

Household members are included in the beneficiary count of dissemination projects as the project is intended to bring changes in their livelihood too.

indicators.title: Number of germplasm (inbreds/hybrids/OPVs, genetic resources, introgression lines) collected and conserved
indicators.description: Living genetic resources such as seeds or tissue (of main crop categories), maintained for the purpose of breeding, preservation, and other research uses, that has been acquired (e.g. from farmer’s fields, CGIAR Centers) and that is being preserved (e.g. in-situ and ex-situ) for future use.

indicators.title: Number of accessions characterized on a phenotypic level
indicators.description: Crops/seeds/lines that have been described by observable physical characteristics using phenotyping.

indicators.title: Number of accessions characterized on molecular level.
indicators.description: Crops/seeds/lines that have been described by biochemical characteristics using either (i) genotyping (i.e. determining differences in the genetic make-up) or (ii) sequencing (i.e. determining the precise order of nucleotides within a DNA molecule).

indicators.title: Number of accessions properly characterised and made available for varietal improvement
indicators.description:
A new germplasm material that has been systematically specified, properly stored and made accessible for enhancement through breeding.
Note: Accession is a unit for conserving germplasm material in a gene bank.

indicators.title: Number of lines deposited with the national gene-bank
indicators.description: Lines are individual of a particular species which are nearly identical/ completely different to each other in genotype due to long term inbreeding.

indicators.title: Number of lines duplicated with the SADC Plant Genetic Resources Center (SPGRC)
indicators.description: Lines that have been deposited by National Genetic Plant Genetic Resources to SADC Plant Genetic Resources Center (SPGRC).

indicators.title: Number of improved maize varieties released
indicators.description: Maize varieties that have undergone independent external evaluation (i.e. tests for distinctiveness, uniformity and stability as well as the value for cultivation and use) leading to its registration by the National Variety Release Committee. The registration establishes legal ownership of the new variety.

indicators.title: Number of improved rice varieties released
indicators.description: Maize varieties that have undergone independent external evaluation (i.e. tests for distinctiveness, uniformity and stability as well as the value for cultivation and use) leading to its registration by the National Variety Release Committee. The registration establishes legal ownership of the new variety.

indicators.title: Number of improved legume varieties released
indicators.description: Legume varieties that have undergone independent evaluation (i.e., tests for distinctiveness, uniformity and stability as well as the value for cultivation and use) leading to its registration by the National Variety Release Committee. The registration establishes legal ownership of the new variety.

indicators.title: Number of improved cassava varieties released
Number of improved agronomic practices developed and formally recommended to the national extension services
indicators.description:
Agronomic practice: Application of a distinct management approach / innovation to enhance crop production (e.g. green manure use, fertilizer application rates, Conservation Agriculture, Water management). Agronomic practices are steps farmers incorporate into their farm management systems to improve soil quality, enhance water use, manage crop residue, and improve the environment through better fertilizer management.
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National Agricultural Research and Extension Services (NARES).

indicators.title: Number of improved pest management practices developed and formally recommended to national extension services.
indicators.description:
“Improved pest management” refers to new methods and approaches for prevention and treatment of pests.
“Pests” are organisms that damage or interfere with desirable crop plants in the fields and orchards, landscapes, or wild lands, or other structures. A pest can be a plant (weed), vertebrate (bird, rodent, or other mammal), invertebrate (insect, mite, or snail) and nematode.
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and Extension Services (NARES).

indicators.title: Number of improved disease management practices developed and formally recommended to national extension services.
indicators.description:
“Improved disease management practices” refer to new methods and approaches for prevention and treatment of diseases.
A “disease” is a pathogen (bacteria, virus, or fungus) infecting a plant and thereby damaging or interfering with the desirable crop growth in the fields and orchards.
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and Extension Services(NARES)

indicators.title: Number of improved water management practices developed and recommended to the national extension services (e.g. moisture conservation technics, irrigation scheduling , irrigation methods)
indicators.description:
“Improved water management practices” refer to efficient use of water for enhanced crop production (e.g. moisture conservation technics, irrigation scheduling, and irrigation methods). Efficient water use implies use of agricultural water saving techniques such as varieties / soil management techniques.
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and Extension Services(NARES)

indicators.title: Number of improved postharvest storage technologies developed and formally recommended to the national advisory service (e.g. post harvest storage facilities, pest management)
indicators.description:
“Improved postharvest storage technologies” are innovations/methods that help to keep harvested produce at a quality level that is adequate for consumption, marketing and processing (e.g. post-harvest storage facilities, pest management).
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and Extension Services (NARES).

indicators.title: Number of improved processing technologies developed and formally recommended to the national advisory service
indicators.description:
Innovations/procedures for modifying /transforming/ value adding to agricultural produce to prolong shelf life, improve quality, availability for income generation.
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and extension services(NARES)

indicators.title: Number of labour saving technologies developed and formally recommended to the national extension services
indicators.description:
Innovations/practices aiming at reducing the manpower/drudgery, reducing cost of production / processing for the agricultural output (e.g., crop, dairy).
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and extension services (NARES).

indicators.title: Number of trial sites established
indicators.description: A trial site is an area that has been selected for the purposes of carrying out a research trial/experiment funded by APPSA. These trial sites include the conservation sites. This indicator will measure the total number of trial sites in all the R & D projects established by RCoL per year.

indicators.title: Number of demonstrations established
indicators.description: A demonstration is a platform where technologies (varieties and management practices) are established to create awareness to stakeholders.

indicators.title: Number of farmers participating in on-farm participatory research
indicators.description: Farmers taking part in agricultural research trials in close collaboration with APPSA funded R&D projects per country.

indicators.title: Number of field days conducted
indicators.description: A field day is platform where technologies are showcased for purposes of creating awareness to the stakeholders, getting feedback and sharing lessons learnt.

indicators.title: Number of farmers participating in field days (by gender)
indicators.description:
Farmers attending field days facilitated by R&D project where technologies are showcased for learning purposes.
Note: A “farmer” is an individual involved in crop and animal production for food, income or raw materials.

indicators.title: Number of fairs held to show case technologies
indicators.description: A fair is a forum for displaying agricultural technologies with the purpose of creating awareness to the stakeholders.

indicators.title: Number of participants attending fairs
Number of extension personnel trained
indicators.description:
An extension personnel is an individual involved in facilitation of agriculture technology transfer 
Capacity strengthening of advisory service providers and lead farmers is another approach for technology dissemination.

indicators.title: Number of lead farmers trained
indicators.description:
Lead farmers trained in APPSA promoted technologies by the RCoL.
“Lead farmers” represent the group of innovative and successful farmers within the local community who are committed to training their fellow farmers on agriculture methods and technologies. Typically, they are selected by the community and registered as lead farmers with the field extension office in a given administrative unit (e.g. district, EPA, block, camp). They are in direct contact with researcher or extension personnel to help champion the demonstration of a technology in their areas.

indicators.title: Number of IEC materials published
indicators.description: Information Education Communication (IEC) materials include brochures, success stories, pamphlets, briefs, extension manuals, flyers, posters, fact sheets and bulletins. The indicator describes IEC materials developed and published by RCoL.

indicators.title: Number of IEC materials distributed
indicators.description: IEC materials include brochures, success stories, pamphlets, briefs, extension manuals, flyers, posters, fact sheets and bulletins printed and distributed by RCoL. The indicator describes Information Education Communication (IEC) materials printed and distributed or shared electronically by RCoL to stakeholders.

indicators.title: Number of sms messages dispatched to lead farmers on promoted technologies
indicators.description: Number of messages (content) dispatched to lead farmers on promoted technologies by the RCoL. The messages can be in different languages.

indicators.title: Number of sms responses by lead farmers
indicators.description: Total number/percentage of responses by lead farmers made to the RCoL.

indicators.title: Number of TV documentaries produced and aired
indicators.description: TV documentaries sponsored by APPSA to reach the target population with a message on a specific technology or practice.

indicators.title: Number of radio programs produced and aired
indicators.description: Radio programs sponsored by APPSA to reach the target population with a message on a specific technology.

indicators.title: Quantity of breeder seed produced
indicators.description: Breeder Seed is produced under direct supervision of the plant breeder and represents the true pedigree of the variety. Normally available in small quantities (Kgs), and is planted to produce foundation/basic seed.

indicators.title: Quantity of foundation/basic seed produced
indicators.description: Foundation/basic Seed is the first generation of seed multiplication using the breeder seed. It is produced under direct control of a seed quality and certification unit or a similar formal entity. It is available in limited quantities, (Kgs) and is planted to produce certified seed.

indicators.title: Quantity of certified seeds produced
indicators.description: Certified Seed is produced from foundation/basic seed. It is available in large quantities (tons), and is sold to farmers for general grain production. Typically it is produced by seed companies, directly or under contract farming.

indicators.title: Number of improved varieties released by the RCoL that can be accessed by farmers
indicators.description:
Certified crop seed varieties that are registered under ZARI/IIAM/DARS and were either generated or disseminated with the help of APPSA research funds.  An improved variety is deemed accessible to farmers if it is available to 40% of the marketing outlets in the target districts
Note: “Accessed by farmers“ means that it can be acquired or purchased on the local market (e.g. stocked with agro dealers, government subsidized inputs)

indicators.title: Number of technologies released by a RCoL in two countries and that can be  accessed by Farmers
indicators.description:
Certified seed varieties, agronomic and postharvest practices that are registered in two APPSA program countries under the name of one of the three institutions ZARI/IIAM/DARS, and which were either generated or disseminated with the help of APPSA research funds.
Note: “accessed by farmers” means that it can be acquired or purchased on the local market (e.g. stocked with agro dealers, government subsided inputs).

indicators.title: Number of APPSA funded R&D projects integrated in existing innovation platforms
indicators.description: An innovation platform is a space for learning and change. It is a group of individuals (who often represent organizations) with different backgrounds and interests including farmers, traders, food processors, researchers, government officials, etc.

indicators.title: Number of improved technologies (varieties/management practices) being promoted to farmers through the existing innovation platforms
indicators.description: An innovation platform is a space for learning and change. It is a group of individuals (who often represent organizations) with different backgrounds and interests including farmers, traders, food processors, researchers, government officials, etc.

indicators.title: Proportion of participatory research projects in RCoL portfolio
indicators.description: Participatory research comprises a range of methodological approaches and techniques, all with the objective of handing power from the researcher to research participants, who are often community members or community-based organizations. In participatory research, participants have control over the research agenda, the process and actions. Most importantly, people themselves are the ones who analyze and reflect on the information generated, in order to obtain the findings and conclusions of the research process.

indicators.title: Number of R&D consultative meetings with stakeholders
indicators.description: A consultative meeting is a forum where stakeholders meet to take stock of achievements, review R&D priorities and plan for the way forward. A broader group of stakeholders includes investors, policy makers, farmers/farmer representative, seed companies, processors, CSOs, NGOs, CGIAR centers, universities etc.

indicators.title: Number of National Steering Committee meetings held
indicators.description: A steering committee is a committee that decides on the priorities or order of business in compliance with its formally agreed Terms of Reference.

indicators.title: Number of infrastructure under construction at RCoL progressing according to plan
indicators.description:
Research Infrastructure” refers to physical structures needed for an improved operation of the RCoL.  For example this can include access roads, greenhouses, laboratories, cold rooms, resource centres, offices, and improvement of field research sites.
“Construction “refers to building a NEW physical structure.

indicators.title: Number of infrastructure under rehabilitation at RCoL progressing according to plan.
indicators.description:
“Research Infrastructure” refers to physical structures needed for an improved operation of the RCoL.  For example this can include access roads, greenhouses, laboratories, cold rooms, resource centres, offices, and improvement of field research sites.
“Rehabilitation” refers to the repair and/or upgrade of existing structures.

indicators.title: Proportion of total US$ invested in the construction of RCoL infrastructure
indicators.description:
“Research Infrastructure” refers to physical structures needed for an improved operation of the RCoL.  For example, this can include access roads, greenhouses, laboratories, cold rooms, resource centres, offices, and improvement of field research sites.
“Construction” refers to building a NEW physical structure.
“US$ invested” refers to total payments made by the RCoL to external entities for rehabilitation of infrastructure since launch of the project.

indicators.title: Proportion of total US$ invested in the rehabilitation of RCoL infrastructure
indicators.description:
“Research Infrastructure” refers to physical structures needed for an improved operation of the RCoL.  For example, this can include access roads, greenhouses, laboratories, cold rooms, resource centres, offices, and improvement of field research sites.
“Rehabilitation” refers to the repair and/or upgrade of existing structures.
“US$ invested” refers to total payments made by the RCoL to external entities for rehabilitation of infrastructure since launch of the project.

indicators.title: Proportion of scientific equipment procured
indicators.description: “Scientific equipment” refers to instruments, apparatus or devices designed to be used in measurements and technology development (e.g. equipment for crop breeding, entomology, plant pathology, pest and disease Identification etc.)

indicators.title: Proportion  of total US$ invested  into procuring scientific equipment for the RCoL
indicators.description:
“Scientific equipment” refers to instruments, apparatus or devices designed to be used in measurements and technology development (e.g. equipment for crop breeding, entomology, plant pathology, pest and disease Identification etc.)
“US$ invested” refers to total payments made by the RCoL to external entities for the acquisition of scientific equipment since launch of the project.

indicators.title: Performance of RCoL Management System
indicators.description:
‘Managerial Performance’ refers to the effectiveness of fulfilling managerial roles and responsibilities.
Managerial performance will be measured as a function of 
•	professional development of staff 
•	 the effectiveness of the Financial management system 
•	 the effectiveness of the procurement system 
•	 the effectiveness of the social and environmental safeguard management system 
the effectiveness of the M&E  management system

indicators.title: The extent to which the SADC variety release system is adhered to at country level
indicators.description:
Adherence to variety release system entails determination of distinctiveness, uniformity and stability (DUS); value for cultivation and use (VCU); and period of testing. If a variety is released in two countries it can be released in another country without testing as long as it appears on the regional register.

Rating: 1 Non-compliant; 2 Partially compliant; 3 Fully compliant

indicators.title: The extent to which the SADC seed certification system is adhered to at country level
indicators.description:
Adherence to seed certification system entails the following: registration of seed crops; passing field inspections and laboratory tests; getting SADC certification; and accessing regional market.

Rating: 1 Non-compliant; 2 Partially compliant; 3 Fully compliant

indicators.title: The extent to which the SADC phytosanitary measures for seed are adhered to at country level
indicators.description: Adherence to phytosanitary measures entails the following: agreement on common disease and pest of regional importance; inspection of field seed crop and seed lots; and SADC certification.

indicators.title: Number of monitoring visits undertaken
indicators.description: A monitoring visit is a routine management tool track progress and adherence to set procedures and guidelines.

indicators.title: Number of technical working group meetings held on M&E
indicators.description: A technical working group comprises technical experts deemed relevant for the program with specific terms of reference

indicators.title: Proportion of recommendations implemented arising from national and regional implementation support missions
indicators.description: An “implementation support mission” is a routine management tool for tracking progress and adherence to set procedures and guidelines.

indicators.title: Number of APPSA supported meetings on Intellectual Property Rights (IPRs) issues
indicators.description: “Intellectual Property Rights” are the protections granted to the creators of IP, and include trademarks, copyright, patents, industrial design results, and in some jurisdiction trade secrets. These property rights allow the holder to exercise a monopoly on the use of the item for a specified period.

indicators.title: Proportion of recommendations from APPSA supported IPR meetings that have been implemented
indicators.description: “Intellectual Property Rights” are the protections granted to the creators of IP, and include trademarks, copyright, patents, industrial design results, and in some jurisdiction trade secrets. These property rights allow the holder to exercise a monopoly on the use of the item for a specified period.

indicators.title: Number of briefs by national seed control systems that address harmonization of seed policies and standards
indicators.description: Text articles, chapters, essays and other content analyzing relevant policies and standards that inform harmonization efforts across APPSA countries (e.g. biosafety regulations, IPR).

indicators.title: Number of varieties released/registered in one partner country and that are eligible for release in another SADC partner country without undergoing testing
indicators.description:
The country of registration is the country where the variety is registered on the National Official Catalogue, following satisfactory tests for distinctness, uniformity and stability. 
Number of varieties accepted by National Designated Authorities as eligible for certification in accordance with the Rules of the SADC harmonized seed regulatory system.

indicators.title: Total # of PhD (% female) scholarship holders funded by the project that have successfully completed long term training
indicators.description: This indicator will track the number of staff trained at PhD level with funding under APPSA. Only people who have completed the full training programme and have been certified as having successfully completed the training programme by the training institution are counted for this indicator.

indicators.title: Total # of MSc (% female) scholarship holders funded by the project that have successfully completed long term training
indicators.description: This indicator will track the number of staff trained at MSc level with funding under APPSA. Only people who have completed the full training programme and have been certified as having successfully completed the training programme bythe training institution are counted for this indicator.

indicators.title: Total # of BSc (% female) scholarship holders funded by the project that have successfully completed long term training
indicators.description: This indicator will track the number of staff trained at BSc level with funding under APPSA. Only people who have completed the full training programme and have been certified as having successfully completed the training programme by the training institution are counted for this indicator.

indicators.title: Number of staff trained per research centre in management and leadership (% female)
indicators.description:
Training is defined as a learning activity for participants involving: 1) a setting intended for teaching or transferring knowledge, skills, or attitudes; 2) formally designated instructors or lead persons; and 3) a defined curriculum, learning objectives, and outcomes.


This indicator will track the number of staff trained in leadership and management. Participants should attend at least 90% of total course hours to be considered as completing a course. People attending more than one training should be counted once for each training they complete.

indicators.title: Number of staff trained per research centre in in administrative processes (incl. FM, HR, Procurement, M&E, safeguards) (% female)
indicators.description:
Training is defined as a learning activity for participants involving: 

1) a setting intended for teaching or transferring knowledge, skills, or attitudes

2) formally designated instructors or lead persons; and 

3) a defined curriculum, learning objectives, and outcomes.


This indicator will track the number of staff trained in administrative processes. Participants should attend at least 90% of total course hours to be considered as completing a course. People attending more than one training should be counted once for each training they complete.

indicators.title: Number of staff trained per research centre in technical research and dissemination (% female)
indicators.description:
Training is defined as a learning activity for participants involving: 

1) a setting intended for teaching or transferring knowledge, skills, or attitudes; 

2) formally designated instructors or lead persons; and 

3) a defined curriculum, learning objectives, and outcomes.


Number of staff trained in technical research and dissemination. Participants should attend at least 90% of total course hours to be considered as completing a course. People attending more than one training should be counted once for each training they complete.

indicators.title: Number of clients (research and advisory service staff) days of training in management and leadership training (% female)
indicators.description: Number of days of training in management and leadership. This indicator uses the following equation to calculate the number of client days of training: (training days) x (number of people completing each training) = Person days of training supported by APPSA. Only people who complete the entire training course are counted for this indicator.

indicators.title: Number of clients (research and advisory service staff) days of training in administrative processes (incl. FM, HR, Procurement, M&E, safeguards) (% female)
indicators.description:
Number of days of training in administrative processes. This indicator uses the following equation to calculate the number of client days of training: (training days) x (number of people completing each training) = Person days of training supported by APPSA. Only people who complete the entire training course are counted for this indicator.

People attending more than one training should be counted once for each training they complete.

indicators.title: Number of clients (research and advisory service staff) days of training in technical research and dissemination (% female)
indicators.description:

This indicator uses the following equation to calculate the number of client days of training: (training days) x (number of people completing each training) = Person days of training supported by APPSA. Only people who complete the entire training course are counted for this indicator.

People attending more than one training should be counted once for each training they complete.
